data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, the code would benefit from modernization to use `Task`/`Parallel` APIs instead of raw threads:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is simpler, uses the thread pool efficiently, and is idiomatic .NET 8 — but it's an optional improvement, not a required migration step.
